T. Pomponius Atticus was well-born, cultured‚ and in possession of a fortune which enabled him to speculate in business enterprises of a novel sort, as well - as in recognized ways, while preserving his position as 'gentleman of leisure and patron of literature. He held himself steadfastly aloof from political life, living abroad a great part of the time, and managed to keep the favor of the prominent men of all factions. He had great business sagacity, and acted frequently in matters of business as Cicero’s agent. Cicero deferred to his judg- ment in literary matters also.
